This paper is about developing an autonomous navigation framework for an unmanned ground vehicle (UGV) to perform inspection tasks in nuclear environments. The paper discusses the use of rich information maps to achieve autonomy, which involves generating a 2D global cost map consisting of obstacle locations for path planning, as well as location and orientation information for objects of interest from the inspector's perspective. This paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category, as it deals with developing an autonomous navigation framework for a UGV. It may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category, as the paper discusses the use of rich information maps to achieve autonomy. Computer Vision (cs.CV) may also be a likely sub-category, as the paper discusses the use of location and orientation information for objects of interest. Systems and Control (cs.SY) and Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) may also be possible sub-categories, as the paper discusses the use of the UGV to perform inspections in nuclear environments, which may involve security and safety considerations.
